 India, Africa, America, Canada, Australia and Britain, illustrating how relations must be analysed for the way in which different colonial contexts define and constitute each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist geography. 0aFeminist theory. 0aGender identity in literature. 0aPostcolonialism in literaturexEnglisch. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aPostcolonialism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aBritish colonialism.  aarchitecture.  aclass.  agender.  alandscape.  anationality.  anineteenth century.  asocial relations.  aspatial relations.  atopography.1 aMills, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779381240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793812/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles